   <mods:abstract>In Jefferson's hand, John Jay's reply to the "Case stated ...by the
            Trustees of the sinking fund"--enclosure in Randolph to John Jay, 29 March 1792 (see
            8634 and 7067). John Jay concludes his discourse on "legal" and "market" values of
            stocks by saying:..."I am of opinion that the words 'if not exceeding the par or true
            value thereof' do not restrain the purchase of any part of the debt of the United
            States, so long as the market price of the same shall not exceed the sum actually due
            from and payable by the United States in discharge of these debts." A note on the last
            page of the manuscript describes the Secretary of State's continued opposition to this
            view.</mods:abstract>
